I am a "war baby" born in 1942, so I have no memory of the Second World War. But, I have had the opportunity to meet those for whom Second World War memories were exceptionally strong.

In the 1970s, I worked with a gentleman who took a holiday in France every June. I asked him why and he said he had been an officer who landed at Juno beach on D-Day and that he had to go to Bény-sur-mer (the Canadian D-Day war grave location) "to be with his boys". To me, he typified what "we remember" means.

Ten years ago, my wife and I were bicycling through a national park in Flanders, Belgium when an "old man" motioned for us to stop to ask us our nationality. When we said Canadian, he started to hum "Oh Canada" and informed us he was alive then because his family had been liberated by Canadian troops. He also typifies what "we remember" means.

Remembrance Day does not glorify war; it commemorates the sacrifice to our country of the fallen and the wounded.

Henry actually had solid grounds for an annulment. His father, Henry VII, arranged a marriage between his eldest son, Arthur, and Catherine of Aragon. A few months afterwards, Arthur died. However, Catherine did not want her marriage annulled. She claimed that she loved Henry; a dubious claim at best, since Henry did not treat her well. It is far more likely that Catherine did not want her daughter, Mary, to lose her place as Henry's only legitimate child. Should Henry remarry and have a son, this son would take precedence over Mary as Henry's heir. 

So, Catherine counter-attacked on two fronts: One based in Church marriage law, the other political. In Church marriage law, in order for a marriage to be valid, two things must happen. The first is an exchange of vows before witnesses, and there was no question that Catherine and Arthur did this. The second is that the marriage must be consummated. Catherine claimed that she and Arthur had never had intercourse. Thus, the dispensation was irrelevant, and her marriage to Henry was, in fact, her first marriage.

IEPs are reviewed and "changed" if necessary.  A student may move to a more restrictive setting and program if needed OR move to a less restrictive setting and program if merited.  The goal being, hopefully, at some future date, the student's reintegration into the "regular" school program.  Indeed, schools need to consider the disruption caused by dysfunctional students in developing and, when needed, modifying IEPs.  If a student is disrupting the education of other students, at some point, that student does, as you suggest, need to be removed from the classroom.  It's important to provide opportunities for growth and improvement, but not at the expense of the other students.  regards, Gary Crum

EMOTIONAL AND BEHAVIORAL DISORDER (EBD).
Definition. 
An emotional and behavioral disorder is an emotional disability characterized by the following: 
(i)  An inability to build or maintain satisfactory interpersonal relationships with peers and/or teachers.  For preschool-age children, this would include 
other care providers.  
(ii) An inability to learn which cannot be adequately explained by intellectual,sensory or health factors.
